Introduction

Housing prices have shown significant fluctuations in growth rates across many countries recently. While housing prices generally trend upwards over time, accurately predicting these changes can be challenging. Various factors influence the demand for a property, and determining which factors are most influential in shaping buyer behavior is particularly difficult because individual buyers have unique preferences, such as the size of the house, location, and more. This project provides a comprehensive approach to house price prediction using regression techniques, demonstrating the process from data collection to model deployment. The dataset used for this analysis contains 545 observations and is sourced from Kaggle.

Objective

The primary objective of this project is to predict house prices based on various features such as the number of bedrooms, number of bathrooms, area of the house,parking and other relevant attributes. This project aims to build a robust predictive model that can accurately estimate house prices, aiding stakeholders such as real estate agents, potential buyers, and sellers.

Data Collection: The dataset used in this project is sourced from the Kaggle House Prices dataset, which contains detailed information on various properties including their sale prices.

Libraries

The following packages are used in this document viz.

  • tidyverse(data manipulation),
  • caret(creating predictive models),
  • randomForest(classification and regression),
  • xgboost(Boosting),
  • gridExtra(Layout),
  • corrplot(visualization) etc.

The dataset contains 545 observations and 13 attributes.Below is a list of the variables with descriptions.

  • Price: Price of each house sold.
  • Area: Total area of the house.
  • Bedrooms: The number of bedrooms in the house.
  • Bathrooms: The number of bathrooms in the house.
  • Stories: The number of stories in the house.
  • Mainroad: Whether the house is connected to the main road (Yes/No).
  • Guestroom: Whether the house has a guest room (Yes/No).
  • Basement: Whether the house has a basement (Yes/No).
  • Hotwaterheating: Whether the house has a hot water heating system (Yes/No).
  • Airconditioning: Whether the house has an air conditioning system (Yes/No).
  • Parking: The number of parking spaces available within the house.
  • Prefarea: Whether the house is located in a preferred area (Yes/No).
  • furnishingstatus: The furnishing status of the house (Fully Furnished, Semi-Furnished, Unfurnished).

Exploratory Data Analysis

Exploratory data analysis (EDA) entails utilizing graphics and visualizations to thoroughly explore and analyze a dataset. The primary objective is to investigate and gain insights into the data variables present, facilitating a comprehensive understanding of the datasets characteristics.

Data Distribution

Data distribution refers to the pattern or arrangement of data values in a dataset. It is a fundamental aspect of data analysis as it provides essential information about how the data is spread across different values. Understanding the distribution of data is crucial for making informed decisions, choosing appropriate statistical methods, and gaining insights into the underlying phenomena represented by the data.

Interpretation: The histogram of the area attribute reflects a distribution with a central peak around the median value of 4,600, showing a concentration of house sizes between 3,600 and 6,360. The right skewness indicated by the mean being higher than the median will be visible as a gradual decrease in frequency towards the higher end of the distribution. This right-skewed pattern will be accentuated by the presence of a few extreme outliers with very large house sizes.

The boxplot illustrates a distribution where most house sizes are clustered between 3,600 and 6,360, with a median of 4,600. The mean being higher than the median suggests a right-skewed distribution with a tail extending towards larger values. The presence of an unusually high maximum value (16,200) indicates some extreme outliers in the dataset, which could be of particular interest for further investigation.

Interpretation:

The boxplot would illustrate that the majority of the data is concentrated around the median value of 3, with a relatively narrow interquartile range and a slight spread towards the maximum value. In complement, the histogram would visually depict this concentration around the central value of 3, while also revealing a distribution with some data points extending towards higher values, indicating a modest rightward skew.

Interpretation: The boxplot would demonstrate that the majority of the data is tightly clustered around the minimum value of 1.000. The first quartile, median, and third quartile all suggest that 50% of the data falls between 1.000 and 2.000, with a significant concentration at the lower end of this range. The box is narrow, indicating a low interquartile range (IQR), and the whiskers extend from 1.000 to 4.000, showing a small amount of data spread beyond the IQR. The median and the mean are relatively close, but the mean (1.286) is slightly higher than the median, which might indicate a slight skew towards higher values.

This distribution suggests that the data is predominantly clustered at the lower end, with fewer occurrences of higher values. The histograms shape is likely to show a peak at 1.000, tapering off as the values increase, indicative of a positively skewed distribution with a longer tail towards the higher end of the scale.

Trend Comparison

Lets see the trend of our data for each predictor

Correlation Between Variables

Correlation among predictors is a crucial consideration in regression. High correlation between predictors can lead to multicollinearity, affecting the accuracy of the regression model. We can use the corrplot() function from the ggplot2 package to visualize and assess the correlation between predictors.

In this section, we will be analyzing the Pearson Correlation between all of our variables.

Interpretation:

Based on the graph, only several variables have positive correlation with Prices, where Area (0.54), Bathrooms (0.52), Stories(0.42) have stronger correlation compared to other attributes.

This indicates that house prices are greatly influenced by the presence of these attributes and not so much affected by other attributes.

Conclusion

Among the models evaluated, the Random Forest model demonstrates the best balance of explanatory power and prediction accuracy, as indicated by its highest R-squared value and lowest RMSE. The Linear Regression model offers a moderate fit, while the XGBoost model, despite its advanced nature, performs less effectively in this case compared to the other models.

  head(400) %>% 
  select(c("price", "area", "bedrooms", "bathrooms", "stories", "mainroad", "guestroom", "basement","hotwaterheating","airconditioning","parking","prefarea","furnishingstatus")) %>%

  geom_point(size = 0.2) +
  geom_smooth(formula = y ~ x, method = "loess") +

        axis.title.x = element_blank(),

set.seed(42)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(data$price, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
trainData <- data[trainIndex, ]
testData <- data[-trainIndex, ]
#linear regression model
# Fit the Linear Regression model on the training data
lm_model <- lm(price ~ ., data = trainData)
# Get the absolute values of coefficients
importance_values <- abs(coef(lm_model)[-1])  # Exclude the intercept

# Sort the coefficients by importance
sorted_importance <- sort(importance_values, decreasing = TRUE)

# Select the top 5 important features
top_5_features <- names(sorted_importance)[1:5]

# Print the top 5 important features
print(top_5_features)
# Create a formula with the top 5 features
formula <- as.formula(paste("price ~", paste(top_5_features, collapse = " + ")))

# Fit a new Linear Regression model using the top 5 features
lm_model_top5 <- lm(formula, data = trainData)
# Predict on the test dataset
predictions <- predict(lm_model_top5, newdata = testData)
# Calculate R-squared
r_squared_linear <- caret::R2(predictions, testData$price)

# Calculate RMSE
rmse_value_linear <- caret::RMSE(predictions, testData$price)
#random forest model
rf_model <- randomForest(price ~ ., data = trainData, importance = TRUE)
varImpPlot(rf_model,type = 1)
# Get feature importance
importance_values <- importance(rf_model)
# Sort the importance values by the %IncMSE column in decreasing order
sorted_importance <- importance_values[order(importance_values[, "%IncMSE"], decreasing = TRUE), ]

# Print the sorted importance values
print(sorted_importance)

# Select the top 5 important features
top_5_features <- rownames(sorted_importance)[1:5]

# Print the top 5 important features
print(top_5_features)# Create a formula with the top 5 features
formula <- as.formula(paste("price ~", paste(top_5_features, collapse = " + ")))

# Fit a new Random Forest model using the top 5 features
rf_model_top5 <- randomForest(formula, data = trainData)
# Predict on the test dataset
predictions <- predict(rf_model_top5, newdata = testData)
# Calculate R-squared
r_squared_rf <- caret::R2(predictions, testData$price)

# Calculate RMSE
rmse_value_rf <- caret::RMSE(predictions, testData$price)
# Convert the dataset to a matrix (excluding the target variable)
train_matrix <- sparse.model.matrix(price ~ . - 1, data = trainData)
test_matrix <- sparse.model.matrix(price ~ . - 1, data = testData)

# Extract the target variable
train_labels <- trainData$price
test_labels <- testData$price

# Prepare DMatrix objects for XGBoost
dtrain <- xgb.DMatrix(data = train_matrix, label = train_labels)
dtest <- xgb.DMatrix(data = test_matrix, label = test_labels)
# Set parameters for XGBoost
params <- list(
  objective = "reg:squarederror",
  eval_metric = "rmse",
  booster = "gbtree"
)

# Train the XGBoost model
xgb_model <- xgb.train(
  params = params,
  data = dtrain,
  nrounds = 100,
  watchlist = list(train = dtrain),
  verbose = 0
)
# Get feature importance
importance_matrix <- xgb.importance(model = xgb_model)
xgb_importance <- xgb.importance(model = xgb_model)
print(xgb_importance)
xgb.plot.importance(xgb_importance)

# Select the top 5 important features
top_5_features <- importance_matrix$Feature[1:5]

# Print the top 5 important features
print(top_5_features)
# Prepare DMatrix with the top 5 features
train_matrix_top5 <- sparse.model.matrix(as.formula(paste("price ~", paste(top_5_features, collapse = " + "))), data = trainData)
test_matrix_top5 <- sparse.model.matrix(as.formula(paste("price ~", paste(top_5_features, collapse = " + "))), data = testData)

dtrain_top5 <- xgb.DMatrix(data = train_matrix_top5, label = train_labels)
dtest_top5 <- xgb.DMatrix(data = test_matrix_top5, label = test_labels)

# Train the XGBoost model using the top 5 features
xgb_model_top5 <- xgb.train(
  params = params,
  data = dtrain_top5,
  nrounds = 100,
  watchlist = list(train = dtrain_top5),
  verbose = 0
)
# Predict on the test dataset
predictions <- predict(xgb_model_top5, newdata = dtest_top5)
